What is pOS ?

pOS is a brand-new operating system with latest modern conception.
In contrast to most other OS, with pOS there are no generation-based
disadvantages or "inflated" sources, but it offers a slim form and innovative
features.  Pre-emptive multitasking, HAL-principles or intuitive operating
elements provide the basis for an effective use of the hardware - since this is
what an operating system is primarily there for.

No matter, whether used in set-top boxes or as an alternative resp. as optimal
supplement to existing operating systems, pOS convinces with its logically
structured conception, with approved as well as with innovative features.

Fields of use

pOS will first be released in a version for 68k-Amigas (including the »Draco«)
and in a version for PowerPCs. For AMIGA-users and -developers is very
important: the system can be installed parallel to the usual Amiga-OS. It is, of
cause, also possible to run pOS completely independent.

Even the use in set-top-boxes is possible without any problem thanks to its
complexity. Being under development for two years now, there will be first
applications in 1997 that will be based on this modern operating system - for
use in set top boxes or PCs for video editing, for video telephones, for simpler
and quicker processing of orders of large publishers, for Internet- and
T-Online-applications, for calling up TV programs ...., several manufacturers
are already interested or are co-operating with proDAD, since the complexity and
modern conception both offer a basis that is unique, in-expensive and easy.

The fact that this OS may run parallel to existing operating systems and also
offers interfaces to the outer world, make it easy for the developers to port
software to it and enables the user to profit from the new advantages without
having to do without the usual or not yet available applications (older
software).

The exclusive advantage "AMIGA"

pOS has been developed on the Amiga,  which thanks to its conception is the
ideal computer for developing such a project.
Furthermore, the AMIGA offers the possibility to easily run both operating
systems in multi-tasking thanks to the AMIGA-OS. This is why the development of
the OS could be done with the usual tools on Amiga-OS-side, an advantage of
which any developer still profits today.  This is an valuable advantage for the
user as well,  who can still use software that has not been further developed as
usual on the Amiga-OS and can at the same time use innovative new developments
under pOS profiting from all its advantages.
The entry or change to this operating system is thus done very smoothly.

Origin and wishes

proDAD being a traditional Amiga software company, have long followed the
development of the Amiga and also the wishes of users and developers. Commodore
already thought of certain innovative things well in advance but never or only
partially could realise them. Examples for this are RTG or the Datatype-concept.
Always thinking as a developer, those things were very useful for our
applications, their (non-)realisation, however, did not help us much... This is
why pOS is to be considered as the modern basis for the realisation of such and
many other individual wishes, inside but also outside of proDADs.

Negative examples of the Amiga-OS, primarily based on the missing further
development, provide another good reason to realise such a project. Things like
the inflexible graphic output, the outdated printer drivers, the lack of
integrated network ability do lead to quasi-standards and thus partially cause
confusion. Here as well, our role as being a software developers is the basis
for the conception. The reason is simple: if WE have to face with additional
efforts, the OTHER developers have the same problem - all share more or less the
same sad lot. This is why we now try to improve the environmental conditions.

Compatibility

The fact of the compatibility is often considered very important. Other
conceptions, however, have shown that compatibility on the user-level causes
disadvantages rather than advantages, especially since disadvantages are ported
as well.
This is why here the starting point is already at the level below, i.e. at the
developer.
Thanks to a 2/3 compatibility to the Amiga-OS, any software written in standard
ANSI C or C++ can run on p-OS after just one single compiler-process
respectively with only few modifications, already then profiting of all
advantages. Of this advantage, however, exclusively the developers of AMIGA
applications do profit.
 The company Haage & Partner in Rosbach, Germany, offers the corresponding
compiler environment with Power-PC-option. So why creating a software for
PowerPC completely new, which due to emulation will be topped at OS-points?

For porting to 68K-software also your usual environment, for cross porting even
from the Amiga-OS may be used. All that is needed are the supplements available
from the EpOS developer support.
With p-OS the latest stage of a development will already profit by only one
single compiling process from the OS-advantages like e.g. the speed or the Look
& Feels!
The user just does an update and will be excited by the new performance of the
product!
During this time, the developers may already integrate the pOS innovations in
some applications and may improve the software, only based on OS-features.

Should then the desire to go to a new platform arise, this will mean just a
small effort for the developer.

With the multi-platform concept it is not important on which platform the
application is to be written but on which platform pOS is presently running...
Multi-platform concept for pOS also means a multi-processor conformity - pOS and
its applications are ready even for this technique in future getting more and
more practicable,

What is the philosophy behind?

 *
With the multi-platform technology in OS, a bigger market opens
 * for developers (more sales, less effort)
 * for users (less isolation, better orientation)
 * for press (more potential readers)

 * Developing software becomes more attractive again, no platform (and its
users) have to be excluded, the scope of users is simply enlarged
 * Different niche computers, users and developers for such markets can again
feel a push, thanks to concentration on the most important - next to the
hardware - on the uniform OS, a clear basis for developers and users.
 * The computer with the best hardware performance will even in partial areas
show its maximum performance. So that a fair and even comparison is now possible
since the basis of the application will always be the same. A computer with e.g.
high graphic performance will then demonstrate its strength and can then
realistically be compared to other computers. (also see RTG).

Multitasking and communication

The best advantage of all, the pre-emptive multi-tasking, has been further
optimised in pOS and has as well been provided with technical cunnings, of which
not only the user but also the developer profits. An example: in pOS all
frequent task-synchronisations are done via semaphores which leads to a better
time response. Furthermore, a rule has been established, saying that a user may
always obtain the highest priority. The "Deadlock"-risk has also almost entirely
been eliminated thanks to semaphore hierarchies. Further to "normal" tasks, pOS
offers "QuickTasks" with an execution almost three times as quick.

Network capability

Network capability is already guaranteed by the operating system and therefore
much easier to configure.
This firm part turns it easier e.g. for third-party manufacturers of remote data
transmission-software to create software for the connection to global or local
networks.

Furthermore, it is much easier to realise projects for conference connection via
remote-networks. An example would be the joint constructing from different
terminals which is of course optimally supported thanks to the already
integrated RTG-features. It would thus be possible to edit from three computers
on one single project, while one computer equipped with e.g. PPC, simultaneously
executes the rendering of this object.An optimal partition of the internal
processes with maximum hardware utilisation and comfort is the result of this
net that can be co-ordinated already from the operating system.
Sharing of peripherals and data are further possibilities simply made accessible
with these resources. In addition, the direct OS network integrity offers an
easier configurability to the user.

Graphic output / RTG

pOS automatically adjusts the graphic output to the output media with the help
of a library. As a side effect, the graphic output (in contrast to the AMIGA
-OS) has become able for 24-BIT and is considerably quicker. The monitor support
has as well turned much more flexible: e.g. several monitors may simultaneously
be used for one user-interface. The output media may also be a part of a network
or even a virtual-reality component. The best thing for the programmer: It is
not him who has to check what the current hardware offers and with much effort
cope with it - the OS does this job for the developer and this way makes the
software development easier here as well, respectively offers the principle of
the consequent use of available hardware.

Optical appearance

The comfort and the optical appearance have been modernised without any loss in
the operating speed and making sure the functionality does not suffer from
graphic improvements.
Click here and here to see some screen shots

Examples:

Animated menus and gadgets provide more clearness. The windows can finally be
moved around with the content visible. The Shell-window has a slide control to
make earlier outputs visible again and the command buffer of the shell can be
pulled up with a pop-up function. All these are aspects supporting the comfort
and the clearness to the user. The above features are partially also optionally
available for the AMIGA-OS, however, the already mentioned disadvantages of the
out-dated conception and the consequential loss in speed and the different over-
or minor compatibilities show again here. This again shows our effort - thinking
as a developer - to provide a uniform, reasonable and future-oriented basis for
other developers and last but not least for the user.

DOS

The DOS is (compared to the AMIGA-OS) much slender which leads to considerably
more speed. For example the complete BCPL-system does no longer exist. The
scanning of directories as well as the read and write accesses have thus been
considerably accelerated. The possibility to automatically compress and
decompress data while reading or writing is already integrated in pOS.By the
way, the partitioning limit is 1,09*10^12 byte (1 terabyte).which in contrast to
most other operating systems impressively underlines the modern conception. For
multimedia and huge data bases this is an advantage which will in future gain
more and more importance.

What does pOS mean for the developer?

Well, we will point out some (to name just a few...) of the advantages arising
for the programmers:
 * 99% compatible libraries and devices for comfortable porting to p-OS; class
administration by OS kernel
 * derivation possible at run time
 * economic object administration concerning memory partitioning and runtime
overhead
 * instances are filtered by the kernel and sent to the class dispatcher.
Advantage: easier programming and therefore less error-vulnerability
 *
graphic flexibility with RTG:
 * specific adjustment to any output media via a RTG-library, that controls the
graphic output in different levels, starting from the simple graphic operation
(without clipping) up to the full integration of the graphic features needed.
This division allows the quick processing with little optimising or the full
hardware-related programming without compromises at maximum performance.
 * more flexible monitor-support e.g. multi-monitor system for larger working
interface and therefore better overview (provided by RTG)
 * subdivision of graphic areas or even mouse positioning when using several
monitors is done by the operating system (RTG)
 * Considerably improved support of the simple-refreshed windows thanks to
simpler and quicker clipping routines. The refresh of an already repeatedly
clipped area is supported and promoted by high-performance OS-routines (too
complicated in the past).
 * The programs are supported by pOS in the graphic conversion (colours, sizes).
Each application may edit any graphic data in TRUE-colour and leaves the
subsequent display on the monitor to the OS. Depending on the graphic output
device (TRUE-colour screen, 256 colour screen, network, printer, ...) the
appropriate driver will automatically do the conversion!
 * Since pOS may run in an AMIGA-OS window (RTG!) the question of porting to pOS
is really simple. This turns the developing very easy. As a nice side-effect,
this ability also serves the user who - with the parallel use of e.g. Amiga-OS
and pOS - obtains a smooth switch from the old to the new software versions...
 * Super-Bitmap much easier e.g. various gadgets can be placed on a super bitmap
which can be scrolled. The movement of co-ordinates from the part of the graphic
output and the information processing is completely administered by the
operating system.
 * Several layers in one window (daughter layers).
Advantage: a separation of a given gadget bar from an entry field can be made by
the operating system. This serves as well the graphic performance because of the
dropping of the manual switching.
 * object-oriented GUI
all visible elements such as text, graphics, animations etc. are objects. These
objects can be combined object-oriented which e.g. allows the very easy creation
of a menu item with integrated animation (modular design). Self-layouting
gadgets being proportionally font sensitive, i.e. no co-ordinate-programming but
hierarchies.
 * special debug-version of pOS:
The software development is much easier since many errors are already analysed
and displayed before a possible crashing of the system. With this, the
crash-reason can already be recognised usefully and comfortably before a crash.
 * pOS provides a standard-prefs program. All data that can be set are edited
via libraries in pOS-Prefs. The programmer does thus not have to create a full
program with repeated functionality for each setting. The whole administration
is already provided by the pOS-Prefs, so that the single setting only has to
execute its own private part.
 * Simpler debugging of programs - an example:
source fragment: {
  ...
  const CHAR *name;
  pOS_FileHandle *FH;
  name=NULL; // *** NULL pointer
  if(FH=pOS_OpenFile(NULL,name,FILEHDMOD_Read)) {
    pOS_CloseFile(FH);
  }
  ...
}
Output in the debug window:
Current: Task=0x7276170 Name=ShowDebug
Error: |pOS_OpenFile| {rp const CHAR*}
var: |name| = 0x0

better software with better debugging, full performance as soon as programming
of the application has been completed.
The programmer is supported by the kernel, which is to improve quality of the
software and to significantly reduce developing time.
Other OS prefer the other, less effective way:
 * runtime security by large-scale crash protection, the consequence
 *
more overhead:
 * loss of runtime performance
 * need of extensive computing capacity
 * extensive memory requirements

